`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
**`overscroll-behavior: contain`** tells the browser: "when this element's scroll reaches its boundary, don't propagate the scroll event up to the parent." Without it, scrolling to the top or bottom of the panel would "chain" into the host page behind it — a jarring UX where the page shifts while you're trying to inspect CSS properties.

This is a single CSS property (no JS needed) and is supported in all modern browsers. The `contain` value specifically traps scroll within the element while still allowing normal scroll behavior inside it — unlike `none`, which would also disable overscroll effects like bounce/rubber-banding.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

The change is on the `panelScrollRef` div in `Overlay.tsx:1696` — the flex-child container with `overflowY: "auto"` that holds all panel content (search bar, sections, etc.).

---

**Asked:** Add `overscroll-behavior: contain` to the panel's scrollable area.
**Did:** Added `overscrollBehavior: "contain"` to the inline style on the scroll container div in `Overlay.tsx` (line 1696), preventing scroll chaining from the panel to the host page.
